><!--EZCODE LINK END--> guided bomb in taking out deep structures. This was developed in a matter of weeks during the first Gulf War and two were dropped operationally on the final day of fighting. The key to this is its high weight and forged steel case, actually a re-worked 8 inch howitzer barrel. <br>
I have read that a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>30,000</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> lb deep penetration bomb is under development and may be operational any day now.<br>
Only B-52s and possibly the B-2 Stealth bomber could carry this. With a few mods, a B-52 could in fact carry three of them. As I said before, if something on the other side of the world absolutely positively has to be smashed flat, the ancient B-52 (which recently celebrated its 50th anniversary) is the way to go. <br>
For the last word in non-nuclear penetration, we would want to attach something like a GBU-28 to the nose of a ballistic missile, giving hypersonic impact velocity. Explosive filling would be superfluous on a device like this, and might even hinder it, since it lowers the cross-sectional density. It could be a solid iron dart, in fact, or a chunk of cast lunar material from the base we might build there if we had nuclear rockets.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3114<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/30/03 7:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bunker Buster</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/story.jsp?story=374182">Cabinet split over threat of nuclear retaliation.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
By Paul Waugh Deputy Political Editor<br>
31 January 2003<br>
<br>
<br>
Clare Short, the Secretary of State for International Development, said yesterday that Britain should not launch a nuclear strike on Saddam Hussein even if the Iraqi leader were to use biological and chemical weapons in a conflict.<br>
<br>
Ms Short also broke cabinet ranks to give her backing to an anti-war demonstration in London planned for 15 February.<br>
<br>
Speaking in the Commons, Ms Short made clear she would be opposed to a nuclear strike against the Iraqi regime. When asked by Tory MPs what would happen if biological or chemical weapons were deployed by Iraq, Ms Short was unequivocal. &quot;I'm not a military planner but I can't see any scenarios ... where contemplating the use of nuclear weapons would be of any use whatsoever,&quot; she said.<br>
<br>
Her remarks directly contradict Geoff Hoon, the Defence Secretary, who said last year that President Saddam &quot;can be absolutely confident that in the right conditions we would be willing to use our nuclear weapons&quot;.<br>
<br>
Ms Short outlined several risks caused by military action in Iraq, including environmental damage and the loss of water, sanitation and food for millions of Iraqis. She said the &quot;horrendous possibility&quot; of chemical and biological warfare was being prepared for in the UK. &quot;What about the people of Iraq? No one can provide them with suits or immunisation. That is [a] horrifying humanitarian possibility.&quot; <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
